00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:17.710
and more resourceful
than she first appeared.

00:08:17.710 --> 00:08:19.800
Let me tell you another
story about her.

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:26.110
In 1814 at a small post station 12
miles outside of St. Petersburg,

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:28.530
Louisa said goodbye to
her husband, John Quincy,

00:08:28.530 --> 00:08:31.470
not knowing when she
would see him again.

00:08:31.470 --> 00:08:32.870
There were tears on her cheek,

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:35.610
cheers of distress,
as well as grief.

00:08:35.610 --> 00:08:38.510
John Quinsy was living Russia
to negotiate the treaty

00:08:38.510 --> 00:08:40.790
that would end the war of 1812.

00:08:40.790 --> 00:08:44.860
And leaving Louisa alone with
her 7 year old son Charles,

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:46.950
in a ruinously expensive city

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:50.900
where she did not speak the
language and had few friends.

00:08:50.900 --> 00:08:53.270
She'd just lost a much
loved daughter

00:08:53.270 --> 00:08:57.430
and she'd not seen her other
two young sons for 5 years.

00:08:57.430 --> 00:08:58.930
Now, she was on her own.

00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:00.380
It would have been hard for anyone,

00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:02.910
but for Louisa the prospect
was really daunting.

00:09:02.910 --> 00:09:06.890
Even in the best of times
Louisa often doubted herself.

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:08.680
She described herself as timid.

00:09:08.680 --> 00:09:10.990
She called one of her
unpublished memoirs

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:13.120
"The Adventures of a Nobody."

00:09:13.120 --> 00:09:15.780
Another was just, "The
Record of a Life."

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:19.770
At the end of the year John Quincy
wrote to Louisa and told her

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:23.630
to pack their things or sell
them and meet him in Paris.

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:24.930
No problem.

00:09:24.930 --> 00:09:28.680
The trip was nearly 2000 miles
over the half thawed land,

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:31.860
devastated by the Napoleonic wars.

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:35.320
She and her tiny son,
armed with his toy sword,

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:37.890
were on the road for 40 days.

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:41.950
And in that time she was
robbed, warned not to continue,

00:09:41.950 --> 00:09:44.620
told that one of her two
male servants, whom she hired

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:47.130
to protect her, had
a local reputation

00:09:47.130 --> 00:09:50.210
as a quote, desperate villain."

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:54.140
She traveled over half
burnt, half empty villages,

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:56.810
over battlefields still
strewn with wreckage.

00:09:56.810 --> 00:10:01.190
She listened to women tell her
stories of rampage and rape.

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:05.550
Halfway through she learned that
the man behind all this, Napoleon,

00:10:05.550 --> 00:10:10.840
had escaped Alba and was
heading, as she was, toward Paris.

00:10:10.840 --> 00:10:13.370
Men were mustering,
readying for war.

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:15.750
Her male servants fled in fear.

00:10:15.750 --> 00:10:19.590
She, on the other hand,
pretended to be Napoleon's sister.

00:10:19.590 --> 00:10:23.010
At one point her carriage
was surrounded by soldiers.

00:10:23.010 --> 00:10:24.770
"Tear them out of the
carriage," they cried.

00:10:24.770 --> 00:10:26.310
"Kill them."

00:10:26.310 --> 00:10:29.260
It was in French, a language
she could understand.

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:30.940
"Long live Napoleon," she yelled,

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:33.670
and waved her handkerchief,
"Long live."

00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:37.340
That was all in French,
but I'm not going to try.

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:38.880
She went on.

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:40.980
What was so remarkable to me

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:44.970
about that journey is not
only how daring it was.

00:10:44.970 --> 00:10:48.170
It's also what she made
of it later in her life.

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:51.440
20 years later she wrote
and account of that trip.

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:54.690
She understood that it
was not only a good story,

00:10:54.690 --> 00:10:59.190
but something that she could use
to illustrate something of herself.

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:04.850
Something of her fortitude,
her curiosity, her resiliency,

00:11:04.850 --> 00:11:08.740
something of herself and
it was something she wrote

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:12.810
that she could use to
show what women could do.

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:19.540
She wanted to show there were not
-- I think her phrase was, "The --

00:11:19.540 --> 00:11:21.870
struck by the imbecility that" --

00:11:21.870 --> 00:11:25.430
something about the public was
always fancying women to have.

00:11:25.430 --> 00:11:29.350
But she also wanted to show
that she was one who was.

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:33.230
Those were her words
and she underlined them.

00:11:33.230 --> 00:11:36.930
That suggests that in her darker
moments she thought she would

00:11:36.930 --> 00:11:38.710
be forgotten.

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:40.910
And for a long time she was.

00:11:40.910 --> 00:11:42.390
When she was mentioned in accounts

00:11:42.390 --> 00:11:45.360
of her more famous
relatives she was a footnote,

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:48.550
half dismissed as sickly and sad.

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:49.940
Some knew better.

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:53.000
John Adams called her
journals, which she sent to him,

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.550
unnecessary of life to me.

00:11:55.550 --> 00:12:00.020
Her grandson, the great historian,
Henry Adams, was fascinated by her

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:02.570
and thought he might
publish some of her papers.

00:12:02.570 --> 00:12:05.510
He copied hundreds of
pages and is possible

00:12:05.510 --> 00:12:07.680
to see their influence
in his own work.

00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:12.320
The first editor of the Adam's
papers, Lyman C. Butterfield,

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:15.000
once wrote, "In the entire span

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:19.940
of the Adam's dynasty no figure
is more central than the wife

00:12:19.940 --> 00:12:22.220
of the second Adam's statesman,

00:12:22.220 --> 00:12:26.650
and yet none is less
known or more elusive."

00:12:26.650 --> 00:12:30.920
She was unknown because for
two centuries she was thought

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:33.750
to exist outside the
bounds of history.

00:12:33.750 --> 00:12:36.430
Those chronicles of deeds and men.

00:12:36.430 --> 00:12:41.400 position:56%
She was elusive too, because she was
contradictory about her importance,

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:45.470
and her family's background,
denied her worth

00:12:45.470 --> 00:12:49.010
and was quick to describe
her doubts.

00:12:49.010 --> 00:12:53.040
Her character was quicksilver and
the roles she held were unofficial.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:57.230
She was an American who was foreign
born, a first lady in a country

00:12:57.230 --> 00:12:59.730
that was not quite
her own and a mother

00:12:59.730 --> 00:13:02.730
who out lived all but
one of her children.

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:05.930
She was torn between cultural
ideals and strong instincts

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:08.080
that she could not ignore.

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:11.480 position:56%
The idea that a woman should wonder
about her independent identity apart

00:13:11.480 --> 00:13:13.610
from her husbands,
apart from her sons,

00:13:13.610 --> 00:13:17.760
apart from her family was
hardly prevalent or desirable

00:13:17.760 --> 00:13:19.810
in the tine in which she lived.

00:13:19.810 --> 00:13:21.110
It could be painful.

00:13:21.110 --> 00:13:24.000
But there was also a
kind of freedom in it.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.970
The other members of the Adam's
family took their identity

00:13:26.970 --> 00:13:29.300
and their duty for granted.

00:13:29.300 --> 00:13:31.750
Facebook for the ages.

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:34.130
She could speak for herself.

00:13:34.130 --> 00:13:36.950
It became her habit,
even her strategy

00:13:36.950 --> 00:13:40.040
to define herself as
not like the Adams's.

00:13:40.040 --> 00:13:43.910
And, yet, in some larger sense,
the Adams family helped instill

00:13:43.910 --> 00:13:47.450
in Louisa what it helped
instill in the young Republic.

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:50.020
A concern for the value
of the individual,

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:54.420
a fascination with human nature
in its various forms and awareness

00:13:54.420 --> 00:13:59.360
of selfish instincts, a suspicion
of power, a respect for traditions

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:03.550
and a willingness to scrutinize
people, especially ones self.

00:14:03.550 --> 00:14:07.010
And it was in the letters she
exchanged with the Adams family

00:14:07.010 --> 00:14:09.220
where she found her voice.

00:14:09.220 --> 00:14:11.660
It was her voice that
first struck me.

00:14:11.660 --> 00:14:17.340 position:56%
As I read her letters I thought to
myself, "Who was this other Louisa?"

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:21.000
They were vivid, propulsive,
urgent, often hilarious.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:25.470 position:56%
She had an eye for the pompous
general, the charismatic politician,

00:14:25.470 --> 00:14:29.430
the dynamics of Washington life,
of the battles in the capital

00:14:29.430 --> 00:14:31.860
and in the parlor where
she once wrote,

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:35.390
"Ladies wars are always
fierce and hot."

00:14:35.390 --> 00:14:39.290
There was nothing settled, nothing
cast in marbled or enshrined

00:14:39.290 --> 00:14:44.670
in posterity about the people she
met and the events she witnessed.

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:46.770
She witnessed so much.

00:14:46.770 --> 00:14:51.020
When John Quincy died some said in
his life once could find history

00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:53.590 position:56%
of the country's first half century.

00:14:53.590 --> 00:14:55.770
Something like that
could be said of her.

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:58.840
She was born only months before
the start of the revolution.

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:00.410
The year she first arrived

00:15:00.410 --> 00:15:03.310
in the United States federal
power passed peacefully

00:15:03.310 --> 00:15:09.020
from the opposition, her
father-in-law, for the first time.

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:10.500
On the day that her daughter died

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:14.090
in St. Petersburg,
Moscow was set on fire.

00:15:14.090 --> 00:15:17.590
When she died the United States
were only a few years away

00:15:17.590 --> 00:15:19.130
from Civil War.

00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:23.230
Part of the pleasure of writing
the book was seeing these events

00:15:23.230 --> 00:15:26.500
through her amazing gimlet eyes.

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:30.250
She was born in 1775 in London.

00:15:30.250 --> 00:15:35.130
Her father was a classic
crafty merchant

00:15:35.130 --> 00:15:40.060
and her mother was vivacious,
charming, socially ambitious.

00:15:40.060 --> 00:15:41.880
Her parents had secrets.

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:44.620
Some of which Louisa
may have sensed.

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:47.260
She spent the American
Revolution as a young child living

00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:51.990 position:56%
in a luxurious mansion in France and
when the war was over she returned

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:55.180
to London where she was
taught to be a lovely ornament

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:57.710
in the language of the day.

00:15:57.710 --> 00:16:00.400
For the most part Louisa
was raised as young, pretty,

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:03.200
wealthy English girls were
raised, only she was told

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:08.340 position:56%
to consider herself an American and
much more importantly, to marry one.

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:11.290
Her relationship with John
Quincy is central to this book.

00:16:11.290 --> 00:16:15.440 position:56%
It was sometimes passionate,
sometimes tender, sometimes fraught,

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:16.740
beginning with their courtship.

00:16:16.740 --> 00:16:21.540
In 1798, when they wed, he made
it clear that he was committed

00:16:21.540 --> 00:16:25.890
to his country and in marrying
her he was committing her too.

00:16:25.890 --> 00:16:29.360
She tried it once to
reform and resisted.

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:31.930
After their wedding she and
John Quincy went to Berlin

00:16:31.930 --> 00:16:34.710
where he was tasked with
negotiating a treaty

00:16:34.710 --> 00:16:38.350
and she was negotiating a royal
court, representing a republic

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:40.640
who had never been in a republic.

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:45.680
When she reached the United States,
with its democratic pretentions,

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:48.900
she would find that navigating this
country was much more difficult

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:51.410
than learning how to
dance with the king.

00:16:51.410 --> 00:16:54.050
It was harder because there
was no room to settle.

00:16:54.050 --> 00:16:58.990 position:56%
She lived in London, France, Berlin,
Russia, Washington, Boston, Quincy,

00:16:58.990 --> 00:17:00.890
and travelled extensively.

00:17:00.890 --> 00:17:05.930
She spent time in apartments,
hotels, houses, docas, cottages,

00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:10.810
the White House, there were ships,
carriages, sleds, coaches, trains,

00:17:10.810 --> 00:17:13.890
steamboats, it might
not be too much to say

00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:18.340
that for long stretches she
lived in traveling cases.

00:17:18.340 --> 00:17:21.200
She often felt that
she didn't belong.

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:23.760
This makes it easy and a
little tempting to dwell

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:26.130
on what makes her elusive.

00:17:26.130 --> 00:17:29.680
But Mr. Butterfield was right
also to call her central.

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:31.230
She was a force.

00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:32.980
Witty and charming and critical

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:36.060
to her husband's diplomatic
and political efforts.

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:39.090
Abroad she won favor
with kings and queens.

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:42.630
At home she sparred and bantered
with leading politicians.

00:17:42.630 --> 00:17:45.790
She presided over weekly dinners
for senators and cabinet members

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:50.050
and dignitaries, giving them
the cover to talk politics

00:17:50.050 --> 00:17:52.970
when politics were a dirty word.

00:17:52.970 --> 00:17:55.430
She set up a kind of
campaign headquarters

00:17:55.430 --> 00:17:57.950
in her parlor one summer
in Philadelphia.

00:17:57.950 --> 00:18:01.260
And she had a series of
weekly parties called,

00:18:01.260 --> 00:18:05.300
Tuesdays at Mrs. Adams, that made
her the dominate social figure

00:18:05.300 --> 00:18:07.520
in Washington.

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:11.210 position:56%
On the morning before one of these
parties, one of the biggest parties,

00:18:11.210 --> 00:18:15.200
the newspapers all ran a
poem, every stanza ended ,

00:18:15.200 --> 00:18:17.380
"All are gone to Mrs. Adams."

00:18:17.380 --> 00:18:20.460
Her party was actually a pretty
brilliant political maneuver

00:18:20.460 --> 00:18:23.620
in siphoning some of the
tension away from Andrew Jackson,

00:18:23.620 --> 00:18:27.250 position:56%
who had become the leading candidate
while her husband's fortunes

00:18:27.250 --> 00:18:28.550
were lagging.

00:18:28.550 --> 00:18:31.270
And it was actually
delightful downstairs

00:18:31.270 --> 00:18:36.090
in the manuscript room there are
in several collections from people

00:18:36.090 --> 00:18:39.610
of that time, there are copies
of the original invitation

00:18:39.610 --> 00:18:42.080
for that event, which
was fun to find.

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:45.970
That was in 1824.

00:18:49.850 --> 00:18:52.910
It was -- and it's also striking
that so many people saved it.

00:18:52.910 --> 00:18:58.760
It was her campaign in
some ways more than his.

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:03.880
At a time of rising popular
sentiment and turmoil

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:07.010
within the political
establishment she understood

00:19:07.010 --> 00:19:10.920
that people are governed by
emotions, as much as laws

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:13.600
and that politics are about people.

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:15.830
Their little passions
and prejudices,

00:19:15.830 --> 00:19:18.280
their feelings of want and hope.

00:19:18.280 --> 00:19:22.590
John Quincy did everything he
could to hide his feelings.

00:19:22.590 --> 00:19:26.220
He even refused to campaign for the
presidency, because he did not want

00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:28.210
to appear to beg for votes.

00:19:28.210 --> 00:19:32.180
He lashed himself in his diary
for his failings, but outwardly,

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:36.200
as a son, Charles wrote,
"He wore an iron mask."

00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:40.320
She understood something else,
a lesson painfully learned,

00:19:40.320 --> 00:19:43.040
ambition could have terrible costs.

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:45.300
At just the moment John
Quincy came into the power

00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:48.300
of the presidency she
felt most powerless.

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:51.790
She was isolated, felt
alone, they fought.

00:19:51.790 --> 00:19:55.590
The children struggled, their
family began to fall apart.

00:19:55.590 --> 00:19:58.780 position:56%
When she and her husband returned
to Quincy she believed that had come

00:19:58.780 --> 00:20:01.850
to live out their days
exhausted and grieving,

00:20:01.850 --> 00:20:03.920 position:56%
self-questioning, self-flagellating.

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:07.560
She thought she sacrificed
much too much.

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:10.600
But she was resilient and,
in fact, the Adams last

00:20:10.600 --> 00:20:12.990
and greatest act had just begun.

00:20:12.990 --> 00:20:15.960
When her husband became one of the
first great anti-slavery leaders

00:20:15.960 --> 00:20:18.700
in Congress she wrestled
with what it meant

00:20:18.700 --> 00:20:21.650
to be a woman, a wife, a self.

00:20:21.650 --> 00:20:25.060
She thought about how to
have faith, what's so fine,

00:20:25.060 --> 00:20:27.100
what to live for and why?

00:20:27.100 --> 00:20:32.900 position:56%
As fantastic as her adventures were,
the real story is of her inner life.

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:35.750
Her biography cannot be
told like her husbands.

00:20:35.750 --> 00:20:38.960
It is a history of
feelings, as well as facts.

00:20:38.960 --> 00:20:41.390
Of questions, as well as answers.

00:20:41.390 --> 00:20:43.830
Of doubt, as well as certainty.

00:20:43.830 --> 00:20:45.840
It is a record of a life.

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:49.110
It is a narrative of a journey
and it is the adventures,

00:20:49.110 --> 00:20:52.450
not of a nobody, but of
an extraordinary woman.

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:55.510
And I would be happy to answer
any questions you all might have.

