And there was a great, you know,
the whole thing, parade, you know,

00:29:13.090 --> 00:29:16.240
thunder, you know, cannons.

00:29:16.240 --> 00:29:21.800
It's actually really interesting,
Charles Adams writes in his diary

00:29:21.800 --> 00:29:24.620
about that day, about the funeral.

00:29:24.620 --> 00:29:29.700 position:56%
I don't know if there was the same
kind of public outpouring, you know,

00:29:29.700 --> 00:29:33.010
outside of Washington for Louisa.

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:35.510 position:56%
I think in some ways Louisa was more

00:29:35.510 --> 00:29:37.680
of a controversial
figure than Dolly Madison.

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:39.370
I know that is true.

00:29:39.370 --> 00:29:41.490
"Everybody loved Dolly",
as Louisa like to say,

00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:44.580
with a somewhat fake
smile on her face.

00:29:44.580 --> 00:29:46.650
Just as Dolly once wrote of her,

00:29:46.650 --> 00:29:49.910
"I hear Mrs. Adams is
keeping up the dissipations."

00:29:49.910 --> 00:29:53.730
As if Dolly hadn't been
quite the hostess herself.

00:29:53.730 --> 00:30:04.090
So, the -- but, yeah, she was
loved by those who knew her,

00:30:04.090 --> 00:30:07.690
but she had not been quite
as formidable a first lady.

00:30:07.690 --> 00:30:13.430 position:56%
She was more a social force before
and after John Quincy was president,

00:30:13.430 --> 00:30:17.380
but not during the presidency.

00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:21.280
But Charles wrote about
that day and, you know,

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:24.680
how overwhelming it had
been and how he was --

00:30:24.680 --> 00:30:26.190
he had wanted something
actually private.

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:29.820
He'd originally thought maybe her
pallbearers should just be members

00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:32.670
of the family and things like
that, and then he realized he had

00:30:32.670 --> 00:30:35.710
to include all these people.

00:30:35.710 --> 00:30:39.110
But the most striking
thing is that he wrote

00:30:39.110 --> 00:30:43.760
about being amidst this
incredible public, you know,

00:30:43.760 --> 00:30:45.730
big celebration of
his mother's life.

00:30:45.730 --> 00:30:48.110
He said, you know, "I've
never felt more alone."

00:30:48.110 --> 00:30:51.200
You know, just, it
was incredibly moving.

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:53.510
Yes.

00:30:53.510 --> 00:30:56.160
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: I've forgotten
my history, was John Adams --

00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:59.890
or John Quincy Adams,
was he a [inaudible]?

00:30:59.890 --> 00:31:02.790
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: Well, it's not
-- yeah, I'm going to say yes.

00:31:02.790 --> 00:31:05.460
He was technically not the
rank of the ambassador,

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:07.130
we didn't have an ambassador
in those days.

00:31:07.130 --> 00:31:09.690
He was Minister of
Planet Potentiary.

00:31:09.690 --> 00:31:12.390
But we can call it ambassador.

00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:14.080
Yes.

00:31:14.080 --> 00:31:16.300
&gt;&gt; Audience Member:
Her religious life?

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:18.570
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: Very
incredibly important to her

00:31:18.570 --> 00:31:23.060
and increasingly so
as she grew older.

00:31:23.060 --> 00:31:25.830
She was -- the question is
about her religious life.

00:31:25.830 --> 00:31:28.050
And she was, I would say,

00:31:28.050 --> 00:31:31.050
idiosyncratic in her
religious beliefs.

00:31:31.050 --> 00:31:32.920
As she put it late in her life,

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:36.820
"I'm not so sure some people
don't think I'm heretic."

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:42.600
You know, she had gone to a convent
school when she was in France

00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:45.330
and really was always
drawn to the --

00:31:45.330 --> 00:31:50.190
and then had been an
Anglican growing up in London

00:31:50.190 --> 00:31:52.990
and was always drawn
to the kind of ceremony

00:31:52.990 --> 00:31:55.350
of the Roman Catholic Church.

00:31:55.350 --> 00:32:00.300
She was never a Catholic, but she
was definitely more Episcopalian

00:32:00.300 --> 00:32:03.340
than the Adams family was.

00:32:03.340 --> 00:32:06.170
She did not like the snuffling

00:32:06.170 --> 00:32:09.510
and note singing and,
you know, meetings.

00:32:09.510 --> 00:32:12.030
She thought the fact that they
called the church service meetings

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:13.470
was terrible.

00:32:13.470 --> 00:32:18.640
So, but she was sort of also
attended any service, you know.

00:32:18.640 --> 00:32:24.630 position:56%
When she was in Russia she was
going to Te Deum, you know, she was,

00:32:24.630 --> 00:32:27.060
you know, she sort of saw it all.

00:32:27.060 --> 00:32:34.500
And she became very very religious,
especially she had a lot of tragedy

00:32:34.500 --> 00:32:40.140
in her life and when she was
older she wrote a lot about god.

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:44.690
I mean, she really almost, like,
would flip a switch, you know,

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:47.780
and start talking about
God and suffering

00:32:47.780 --> 00:32:49.490
in kind of religious terms.

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:52.640
And I actually didn't really
understand some of her letters

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:57.820
until I was reading the psalms and
I realized that she was really kind

00:32:57.820 --> 00:33:04.180
of borrowing a lot from some of
that metaphors and the language.

00:33:04.180 --> 00:33:06.480
Yeah.

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:09.610
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: Yeah?

00:33:09.610 --> 00:33:11.380
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: Can you say
something more about the sources.

00:33:11.380 --> 00:33:14.680
Are the letters here
or the Adams papers.

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:15.980
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: Both.

00:33:15.980 --> 00:33:20.320
I mean, the Adams papers in the
Mass Historical Society are --

00:33:20.320 --> 00:33:22.590
would be this immense collection.

00:33:22.590 --> 00:33:25.380
It's like 608 -- that might
not be the exact number,

00:33:25.380 --> 00:33:29.500
but something like that -- reels
of microfilm, but there is a set

00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:31.190
of that microfilm downstairs.

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:38.750
There's I think like 50 or
so of them around the world.

00:33:38.750 --> 00:33:43.060
And they've also done a really
wonderful job of digitizing,

00:33:43.060 --> 00:33:44.450
you know, most of their collection,

00:33:44.450 --> 00:33:48.110
so all of John Quincy's diary
is not searchable online,

00:33:48.110 --> 00:33:49.880
but searchable by date.

00:33:49.880 --> 00:33:51.990
Which is amazing.

00:33:51.990 --> 00:33:57.050
And then downstairs there's a
smaller Adams collection of papers.

00:33:57.050 --> 00:34:00.200
And then there are also, you
know, she's friends with people

00:34:00.200 --> 00:34:04.610
like the Thorntons, who was a
great architect at the time,

00:34:04.610 --> 00:34:05.910
so they have collections.

00:34:05.910 --> 00:34:10.950
Or Margaret Bayard Smith, I
think her papers are here.

00:34:10.950 --> 00:34:15.780
Yeah. And, so, there's a lot of
like ancillary material here,

00:34:15.780 --> 00:34:20.460
as well as some original
stuff downstairs.

00:34:20.460 --> 00:34:23.340
Then, you know, you come across
things -- I mean, I was --

00:34:23.340 --> 00:34:26.830
I had such a kind of
an amazing experience

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:30.640
at the Mass Historical Society
keeps a basically a database

00:34:30.640 --> 00:34:33.570
of every Adams letter ever written

00:34:33.570 --> 00:34:36.310
and it's coded by place
and everything.

00:34:36.310 --> 00:34:39.930
And I came across a huge trove
that were not in that database

00:34:39.930 --> 00:34:43.670
at the Historical Society in
Pennsylvania, because it was in --

00:34:43.670 --> 00:34:46.010
she was very good friends
with someone

00:34:46.010 --> 00:34:49.650
who later became a
Supreme Court Justice

00:34:49.650 --> 00:34:52.660
and so it was a man
of some important.

00:34:52.660 --> 00:34:57.760
And his papers were there
and there was a box marked --

00:34:57.760 --> 00:34:59.970
that was called, "Letters
from Ladies."

00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:02.160
And it had obviously not been
open since they were put in.

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:05.000
and there was just
this pile of letters

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:09.220
from Louisa Katherine
Adams right in there, so.

00:35:09.220 --> 00:35:10.680
Yeah. Yep.

00:35:10.680 --> 00:35:14.050
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: If you
were ever in a position

00:35:14.050 --> 00:35:17.460
to actually interview her
personally, what would be a couple

00:35:17.460 --> 00:35:19.350
of the questions you would ask her?

00:35:19.350 --> 00:35:21.000
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: That's not a
question I've ever gotten before,

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:24.580
so I'm not prepared
for this question.

00:35:24.580 --> 00:35:26.970
But, I guess I would --

00:35:30.250 --> 00:35:32.230
I'm not so sure, you
know, I'm not always --

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:36.380
I'm convinced that she's the most
reliable narrator of her own life,

00:35:36.380 --> 00:35:39.480
so it would be interesting
to hear what she would say

00:35:39.480 --> 00:35:41.470
on any number of subjects.

00:35:41.470 --> 00:35:48.110
But, I think I would as her --
there were certain things I wanted

00:35:48.110 --> 00:35:49.580
to know if she knew, you know?

00:35:49.580 --> 00:35:54.040
I wanted to know if she
knew more about her mother

00:35:54.040 --> 00:35:57.380
than she let on or her parents.

00:35:57.380 --> 00:36:03.520
Because I think that does actually
change the story a little bit,

00:36:03.520 --> 00:36:04.820
you know?

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:06.120
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: Why?

00:36:06.120 --> 00:36:10.180
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: Well, her parents
weren't married when she was born

00:36:10.180 --> 00:36:13.940
and it's unclear whether
or not she knew that.

00:36:13.940 --> 00:36:18.610 position:56%
That actually became -- that was
actually brought up in the campaign,

00:36:18.610 --> 00:36:21.930
in the reelection campaign.

00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:24.130
Among -- there was a mudslinging.

00:36:24.130 --> 00:36:27.110
You think elections today is bad.

00:36:27.110 --> 00:36:30.060
And it was incredibly
painful to her and I wonder

00:36:30.060 --> 00:36:32.140
if she knew whether
or not it was true.

00:36:32.140 --> 00:36:38.650
You know, I want to -- she once
wrote that her mother was --

00:36:38.650 --> 00:36:43.320
there was this misconception
that her mother was very --

00:36:43.320 --> 00:36:49.310
was 15 when she first had her first
child with Louisa's sister, Nancy.

00:36:49.310 --> 00:36:53.570
And this is basically under
girded a lot of the scholarship

00:36:53.570 --> 00:36:54.900
that had been done about Louisa.

00:36:54.900 --> 00:36:58.870
That Louisa must have known
that her mother was kind of --

00:36:58.870 --> 00:37:01.330
and if she was 15 she was
probably poorly educated

00:37:01.330 --> 00:37:05.090
or probably lower class and nothing
was known about her mother really.

00:37:05.090 --> 00:37:09.570 position:56%
And there was some sense that Louisa
was very insecure about her mother.

00:37:09.570 --> 00:37:11.530
That's actually not true.

00:37:11.530 --> 00:37:17.760
It turns out, you know, one of
the nice discoveries was be able

00:37:17.760 --> 00:37:21.140
to actually find her mother's
birth records and things

00:37:21.140 --> 00:37:24.250
like that in parish registers.

00:37:24.250 --> 00:37:26.200
And since her mother was much --

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:27.780
and then reconstruct the map

00:37:27.780 --> 00:37:29.540
of who her family was
and who her father was.

00:37:29.540 --> 00:37:32.020
And her, you know, her mother
was pretty middle class.

00:37:32.020 --> 00:37:35.440
Was 23, not 15.

00:37:35.440 --> 00:37:37.040
You know, all these things.

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:43.790
I kind of want to know why she said
her mother was 21 when they went

00:37:43.790 --> 00:37:47.020 position:56%
to France, which would have made her
15 when they had their first child.

00:37:47.020 --> 00:37:51.190
I have an actual theory which is
that Louisa was 21 when she went

00:37:51.190 --> 00:37:54.070
to Prussia and I think
she was just --

00:37:54.070 --> 00:37:57.470 position:56%
when she was writing her own account
she was sort of putting herself

00:37:57.470 --> 00:38:00.170
in her mother's place, or
putting her mother in her place.

00:38:00.170 --> 00:38:01.690
That's -- No, no, no.

00:38:01.690 --> 00:38:03.470
That's complete speculation
on my part.

00:38:03.470 --> 00:38:04.770
That's what I'm saying.

00:38:04.770 --> 00:38:06.710
That's not in the book, you
know, that's me standing up here

00:38:06.710 --> 00:38:12.010
and coming up with a theory
that I can't ever confirm or --

00:38:12.010 --> 00:38:14.670
but that's why I would
have to ask her, you know.

00:38:14.670 --> 00:38:16.050
And I'm not sure she'd
tell me the truth.

00:38:16.050 --> 00:38:18.970
So, but, yeah.

00:38:23.150 --> 00:38:26.600
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: What was
her relationship to her family?

00:38:26.600 --> 00:38:30.920
Did they support her and did
she communicate with the family?

00:38:30.920 --> 00:38:33.600
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: She was very
very close to her sisters,

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:37.000
they were her best -- and had the
typical siblings relationships,

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:40.770 position:56%
fraught relationships with them too.

00:38:40.770 --> 00:38:45.320
She was -- idolized her father.

00:38:45.320 --> 00:38:50.920
And that's partly because,
I think, he had some trouble

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:53.380
that affected her and
she kind of built him

00:38:53.380 --> 00:38:57.710
up in her mind in a
very defensive way.

00:38:57.710 --> 00:39:01.990
But, yeah, I mean, she had a --

00:39:01.990 --> 00:39:07.670
one of the ways in which she
kept her sense of herself intact,

00:39:07.670 --> 00:39:11.770
you know, by being a not Adams,
was that she was Johnson, you know,

00:39:11.770 --> 00:39:16.390
and she sort of held onto that
part of her a little bit tighter

00:39:16.390 --> 00:39:17.960
than was common at the time.

00:39:17.960 --> 00:39:20.790
And it's common for -- when you
marry into the Adams family it was

00:39:20.790 --> 00:39:24.600
like a, pfft, you know,
it was all consuming.

00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:30.580
And she kind of kept some distance
and partly that was by, you know,

00:39:30.580 --> 00:39:33.890
she would sort of write things
like, "Well they, you know,

00:39:33.890 --> 00:39:36.560
my father was a revolutionary
hero too."

00:39:36.560 --> 00:39:43.220 position:56%
You know, she sort of made a kind of
bigger deal out of her bona fides,

00:39:43.220 --> 00:39:46.630
you know, than she
might have otherwise.

00:39:46.630 --> 00:39:48.710
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: How
did she meet Quincy?

00:39:48.710 --> 00:39:51.540
&gt;&gt; Louisa Thomas: Her father was
the American Counsel in London

00:39:51.540 --> 00:39:54.150
and John Quincy -- and his
house was known to be a place,

00:39:54.150 --> 00:39:57.560
it was very welcoming to Americans
who were visiting London, you know,

00:39:57.560 --> 00:39:59.630
you come get your mail,
you talk business.

00:39:59.630 --> 00:40:02.740
It was especially known
to be welcoming

00:40:02.740 --> 00:40:05.070
to young American bachelors
because he had

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:07.290
so many pretty young daughters.

00:40:07.290 --> 00:40:11.150
They would come to pick up their
mail and then stay for dinner

00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:14.350
and then after dinner there
would be singing in the parlor

00:40:14.350 --> 00:40:19.170
by the young soprano Louisa,
and the piano player Nancy

00:40:19.170 --> 00:40:21.190
and Caroline played the harp.

00:40:21.190 --> 00:40:26.930
And, so, it -- you know, there
house was very very social spot.

00:40:26.930 --> 00:40:32.070
So, John Quincy came one day,
brought by John Trumbull,

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:37.770
Colonial Trumbull who painted
all those amazing scenes.

00:40:37.770 --> 00:40:41.860
Who once had a thing
for Louisa himself.

00:40:41.860 --> 00:40:46.040
And he kind of went away for
a month and then came back

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:48.740
and then came back night
after night after night.

00:40:48.740 --> 00:40:53.430
And it's actually very
funny, he couldn't stay away

00:40:53.430 --> 00:40:57.380
and he was suspicious of
pleasure, he was so, in some ways,

00:40:57.380 --> 00:41:01.510
more puritan than, you know,
puritan and he would write

00:41:01.510 --> 00:41:04.390
in his diary like, "This is
terrible, I have to get away,

00:41:04.390 --> 00:41:07.730
